 On Wednesday, NASA announced that there was a problem with one of the International Space Station's cooling systems, which may require a repair spacewalk. The problem doesn't represent a life-threatening emergency, but it has required a cutback in normal operations on the orbiting outpost. The cooling system is one of the "Big 14" maintenance issues that NASA and its partners expect to face on an occasional basis during space station operations. The issue was caused by a malfunctioning flow control valve for the station's ammonia coolant. Engineers are trying to determine whether a software fix can get the valve working again, or whether a spacewalk will be required. The space station's crew worked to keep the freezers going, and the problem is expected to take a couple of days to sort out.

In other news, NASA scaled back operations on the International Space Station after discovering a problem with a cooling system. A pump on one of the station's two external cooling loops shut down after hitting a temperature limit, and teams worked to get the cooling loop back up and running. Experts suspect a malfunctioning valve may have caused the problem, but they're still trying to figure out how to fix it. The station and crew aboard were never in any danger, and officials could determine that an emergency spacewalk is the best way to fix the failed pump. There has been no decision on the spacewalk yet, and it may be a couple of days before the decision is made.

The International Space Station is a $100 billion-plus station that has been continuously occupied since 2000 by spacefliers who spend tours of duty generally lasting four to six months. The current plan calls for the space station to be maintained through 2020, although the United States and the 14 other countries supporting the station project are already considering extending its operating life. The space station includes several large modules, each launched separately and connected in space by astronauts, and it relies heavily on ships to bring up supplies. The space station's life support system is still up and running, and the current mission of the space station is scheduled to go until March 2014. The six-person crew consists of NASA astronauts Mike Hopkins and Rick Mastracchio of the United States;
